--- !u!114 &2214711422301057105
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 3318333350406106248}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 29b480dc3b7c34901916c4e135caebb1, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::ArtifactController
  artifactData:
    description: "The Mbari house is a sacred, temporary architectural form unique
      to the Owerri-Igbo of southeastern Nigeria. It is not a shrine for regular
      worship, but rather a monumental sacrifice in the form of a building, traditionally
      constructed to appease the earth goddess, Ala, following a community catastrophe
      such as famine or war.\n\nOrigins and Purpose\nDivine Command: Construction
      typically began after a diviner (dibia) indicated that a major deity, most
      often Ala, demanded an Mbari to restore peace and fertility to the community.\n\nSacrificial
      Nature: Unlike most architecture, Mbari houses were built to decay. Once the
      elaborate ritual of building was complete, the structure was abandoned to the
      elements, symbolizing the return of all things to the earth.\n\nCommunal Effort:
      While directed by a master artist, the building process was a massive communal
      undertaking involving \"spirit workers\" (Ndi Mgbe) selected by divination
      who lived in seclusion for one to two years to complete the task.\n\nArchitectural
      & Artistic Features\nMbari houses are known for their vibrant, \"rococo-like\"
      complexity, blending architecture, sculpture, and painting.\n\nStructure: They
      are typically open-sided, square-planned shelters made of anthill clay with
      thatched roofs. They often feature a two-story central vault and four columns,
      reflecting the symbolic importance of the number four in Igbo culture (representing
      the four days of the Igbo week).\n\nTableaux of Life: The interior is filled
      with life-sized, brightly painted mud sculptures. These include:\n\nDeities:
      Central figures like Ala (often depicted with a sword or child) and Amadioha
      (god of thunder).\n\nDaily Life: Scenes of childbirth, farmers, craftsmen,
      and even modern figures like policemen, doctors, or automobiles, reflecting
      the community\u2019s evolving reality.\n\nMythology: Legendary creatures, monsters,
      and \"white walkers\" (Europeans) were also commonly depicted.\n\nHistorical
      Decline and Modern Legacy\nThe tradition began to fade in the 20th century
      due to several factors:\n\nColonialism & Christianity: British rule and the
      spread of Christianity led many to abandon traditional ritual practices, viewing
      them as \"pagan\".\n\nThe Biafran War: The Owerri region was a central battleground
      during the Nigerian Civil War (1967\u20131970). The resulting famine and loss
      of life decimated the population of trained artists and the communal wealth
      required for such projects.\n\nIntellectual Revival: Although the physical
      ritual has nearly vanished, the philosophy inspired the Mbari Club in 1961\u2014a
      famous center for African writers and artists (including Chinua Achebe and
      Wole Soyinka) who used the name to represent \"creation\" and \"renewal\"."
